Rawson, who practiced medicine in Richfield 1824+ for 40 years, a relative of the Hooker-Rawson line?","status":"open","notes":"Richfield Township history mentions 'Dr. Secretary Rawson' as Richfield's first physician from 1824, practicing 40 years. Known for temperance work, teaching at Richfield Academy, and founding the town's first library 1825. 'Secretary' is an unusual given name. The Hooker-Rawson line has many gen 5-6 members (HD0299 Nathan Rawson, HD0304 Stephen Rawson, HD0305 Asa Rawson b.1775) — a physician among them migrating to Ohio is plausible. Needs: Rawson genealogy search for any physician named Secretary or with a name that could be a nickname; Richfield Academy records; Ohio medical licensing records 1820s."}],"bio":{"display_name":"John Newton","first_name":"John","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST0045"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Married a Hooker descendant for double-line children","body":"He married Laura Hooker Thompson in 1810 — both bride and groom were 6th-generation descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker through entirely separate lines. Their children descend doubly: through the Newton-Hooker line and through the Hooker-Cowles line."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Connecticut farmer who carved out an Ohio town","body":"He removed from Goshen, Connecticut to Richfield Township in Summit County, Ohio sometime before the 1820s. By that decade he had purchased most of the land around Richfield's east center, building the homestead later owned by Homer Carter."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Brought his widowed mother west to Ohio","body":"His mother Rebecca Minott Newton lived with him in Richfield in her widowhood before moving on to live with his brother Eben in Canfield, Ohio. Both sons had migrated to the Western Reserve."}],"slug":"john-newton-1787"},"HD2915":{"id":"HD2915","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"male","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1811,"month":6,"day":12,"city":"Goshen","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1874},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2925","mother_id":"HD0532"},"marriages":[],"tags":["double_hooker_ancestry"],"sources":[{"short":"Cowles Genealogy #682"},{"bib_id":"BIB003"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Marcus Newton","first_name":"Marcus","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"marcus-newton-1811"},"HD2916":{"id":"HD2916","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"male","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1813,"month":12,"day":19,"city":"Goshen","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1896},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2925","mother_id":"HD0532"},"marriages":[],"tags":["double_hooker_ancestry"],"sources":[{"short":"Cowles Genealogy #682"},{"bib_id":"BIB003"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Lucius Newton","first_name":"Lucius","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artwo